dfischer.utils

Interface GenericPluginInterface

  • All Known Subinterfaces:
    LoadtestPluginInterface, WebSocketPluginInterface

    public interface GenericPluginInterface
    The generic plug-in interface allows to enhance the Proxy Sniffer product with own written utilities. Plug-ins must always be precompiled Java classes which are located in the <MyTests>/Plugins directory of Proxy Sniffer. The type of a plug-in defines under which circumstances a plug-in can be used.

    The following plug-in methods must always return a valid result - even if configure() or construct() never was called before - similar to static methods:

    • getPluginType()
    • getPluginName()
    • getPluginDescription()
    • getInputParameterLabels()
    • allowOptionalInputParameter()
    • getOutputParameterLabels()
    • allowOptionalOutputParameter()
    Load test plug-ins (TYPE_LOADTEST_EXEC) should also implement additionally the following static-like methods from the LoadtestPluginInterface:
    • getAllowedConstructScope()
    • getAllowedExecScope()
    • getAllowedExecOrder()
    • allowMultipleUsage()
    • getFixedUserInputFields()
    All other methods are executed only at runtime when the plug-in is used - called in the following sequence:
    • construct(context)
    • setInputParameter(parameterNumber, parameterValue)
    • execute(context)
    • getLogVector()
    • getOutputParameter(parameterNumber)
    • deconstruct(context)
    Notice: plug-ins must always have a public default constructor without any parameters which must not be enhanced with initial code. This default constructor is already called when the plug-in is configured on the Web Admin GUI. The "normal" constructor which is executed at runtime is the method construct().
    See Also:
    LoadtestPluginInterface, LoadtestPluginContext

    • Field Detail

      • TYPE_LOADTEST_EXEC

        static final int TYPE_LOADTEST_EXEC
        Plug-in Type Definition: the plug-in is a loaded and executed during a load test. The plug-in can be optionally bound at the GUI to an emulated user or to a particular URL call. Interactions with var handler variables are supported (reading and writing from/to variables). This means that the parameter values of the methods setInputParameter(nr, object) and getOutputParameter(nr) must be processed as a string object

        A copy of the plug-in(-class) will be created inside the same directory where the Java load test program will be created (old plug-in versions are overwritten). The plug-in must be zipped together with the compiled load test program before a test-run can be started.

        See Also:
        LoadtestPluginInterface, getPluginType(), Constant Field Values

      • getPluginName

        java.lang.String getPluginName()
        Returns the name of the plug-in which is shown at the GUI. The length of the name should not exceed 30 characters. This method must return a valid (fixed) result even when configure() or construct() never was called before.
        Returns:
        the name of the plug-in

      • getPluginDescription

        java.lang.String getPluginDescription()
        Returns the description (help text) of the plug-in which is shown at the GUI. Several text-lines can be separated by <nl> characters. The description must be plain text, HTML formatting is not supported. This method must return a valid (fixed) result even when configure() or construct() never was called before.
        Returns:
        the description of the plug-in

      • construct

        void construct(java.lang.Object context)
        Triggers the plug-in to initialize itself at runtime. This method will be called before execute() is called.
        Parameters:
        context - the plug-in specific context (depending on the plug-in type), or null if no context is available
        See Also:
        LoadtestPluginContext

      • getInputParameterLabels

        java.lang.String[] getInputParameterLabels()
        Returns an array with the names of all plug-in input parameters. These names are shown at the GUI. An empty array should be returned if no input parameters are needed. This method must return a valid (fixed) result even when configure() or construct() never was called before.
        Returns:
        an array with all names of the plug-in input parameters

      • allowOptionalInputParameter

        int allowOptionalInputParameter()
        Returns the number of the input parameter, starting from which one all succeeding input parameters are optional.
        Returns:
        the number of the input parameter, starting from which one all succeeding input parameters are optional, or -1 if all input parameters are required.

      • setInputParameter

        void setInputParameter(int parameterNumber,
                     java.lang.Object parameterValue)
        Sets the value of a plug-in input parameter at runtime.
        Parameters:
        parameterNumber - 0, 1, 2 ...
        parameterValue - the value of the input parameter, the data type of the input parameter depends on the plugin type.

        java.lang.String[] getOutputParameterLabels()

        Returns:
        an array with all names of the plug-in output parameters

      • getOutputParameter

        java.lang.Object getOutputParameter(int parameterNumber)
        Returns the value of a plug-in output parameter at runtime. This method will be called after execute(). The data type and formatting of the output parameter depends on the plug-in type.
        Parameters:

        Returns:
        the value of the output parameter, or null if the parameter number is out of range - or if no value is available for the output parameter

      • getLogVector

        LogVector getLogVector()
        Returns the internal log vector of the plug-in which can be used for debugging purposes. A new log vector should be made available by the plug-in each time when execute() is called.
